NAME
    awk - pattern scanning and processing language

SYNOPSIS
    awk [OPTION]... PROGRAM [FILE]...
    awk [OPTION]... -f PROGRAM-FILE [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
    awk scans each input FILE (or stdin) line by line and, for each line,
    tests whether it matches any of a set of patterns. For each matched
    pattern, the associated action is executed.

    A PROGRAM is a sequence of pattern-action pairs:
        pattern { action }
    If pattern is omitted, the action executes for every line.
    If action is omitted, matching lines are printed.

    Special patterns:
        BEGIN   Action executed before any input is read.
        END     Action executed after all input is consumed.

OPTIONS
    -F FS, --field-separator=FS
        Use FS as the input field separator (default: whitespace).

    -v VAR=VALUE, --assign=VAR=VALUE
        Assign VALUE to variable VAR before program execution.

    -f FILE, --file=FILE
        Read awk program from FILE instead of command line.

    --version
        Output version information and exit.

    --help
        Display help and exit.

BUILT-IN VARIABLES
    FS      Input field separator (default: space/tab runs).
    OFS     Output field separator (default: ' ').
    RS      Input record separator (default: newline).
    ORS     Output record separator (default: newline).
    NR      Current record (line) number across all files.
    NF      Number of fields in current record.
    FNR     Record number within current file.
    FILENAME  Name of current input file.

BUILT-IN FUNCTIONS
    print [EXPR,...]      Print to stdout.
    printf FORMAT, ...    Formatted output.
    length([STR])         String length or length of $0.
    substr(STR, M [, N])  Substring starting at M, length N.
    index(STR, SUB)       Position of SUB in STR (1-based), 0 if absent.
    split(STR, ARR [, FS]) Split STR into array ARR; return count.
    sub(RE, REP [, STR])  Replace first match of RE with REP.
    gsub(RE, REP [, STR]) Replace all matches of RE with REP.
    match(STR, RE)        Set RSTART/RLENGTH; return start pos or 0.
    tolower(STR)          Return lowercase copy.
    toupper(STR)          Return uppercase copy.
    int(EXPR)             Truncate to integer.
    sqrt(EXPR)            Square root.

EXAMPLES
    awk '{print $1}' file.txt
        Print first field of every line.

    awk -F: '{print $1, $3}' /etc/passwd
        Print username and UID from passwd file.

    awk '/error/ {print NR": "$0}' log.txt
        Print matching lines with line numbers.

    awk '{sum += $1} END {print sum}' nums.txt
        Sum the first column.

    awk 'NF > 0' file.txt
        Remove blank lines.

    awk -v OFS=, '{print $1,$2,$3}' data.txt
        Reformat fields with comma separator.

EXIT STATUS
    0   Success.
    1   Error in program or I/O error.
